We can build two matrix representations of T, one relative to B and one relative to C.  Each is easy, but for wildly different reasons.  In our computation of the matrix representation relative to B we borrow some of our work in .  Here are the representations, then the explanation.  We have
                \vectrep{B}{\lteval{T}{\vect{x}_1}}
                &=
                \vectrep{B}{2\vect{x}_1}
                =\vectrep{B}{2\vect{x}_1+0\vect{x}_2+0\vect{x}_3+0\vect{x}_4}
                =\colvector{2\\0\\0\\0}
                \vectrep{B}{\lteval{T}{\vect{x}_2}}
                &=
                \vectrep{B}{2\vect{x}_2}
                =\vectrep{B}{0\vect{x}_1+2\vect{x}_2+0\vect{x}_3+0\vect{x}_4}
                =\colvector{0\\2\\0\\0}
                \vectrep{B}{\lteval{T}{\vect{x}_3}}
                &=
                \vectrep{B}{(-1)\vect{x}_3}
                =\vectrep{B}{0\vect{x}_1+0\vect{x}_2+(-1)\vect{x}_3+0\vect{x}_4}
                =\colvector{0\\0\\-1\\0}
                \vectrep{B}{\lteval{T}{\vect{x}_4}}
                &=
                \vectrep{B}{(-2)\vect{x}_4}
                =\vectrep{B}{0\vect{x}_1+0\vect{x}_2+0\vect{x}_3+(-2)\vect{x}_4}
                =\colvector{0\\0\\0\\-2}
            .

So the resulting representation is
                \matrixrep{T}{B}{B}
                =
                \begin{bmatrix}
                2 & 0 & 0 & 0\\
                0 & 2 & 0 & 0\\
                0 & 0 & -1 & 0\\
                0 & 0 & 0 & -2\\
                \end{bmatrix}
            .

Now for the matrix representation relative to C first compute,
                &\vectrep{C}{\lteval{T}{\vect{y}_1}}
                =\vectrep{C}{\begin{bmatrix}-17&-57\\-14&-41\end{bmatrix}}\\
